[3]
Date: Sat 10 Jul 2010
Source: The Veterinary Record 167: 69 (2010), letters [edited]


_Staphylococcus aureus_ ST49 infection in red squirrels
-----------------------------------------------------
[Authors: V Simpson, N Davison, L Hudson, and AM Whatmore]

A paper in this issue of Veterinary Record describes dermatitis in
red squirrels (_Sciurus vulgaris_) (Simpson and others, pp 59-62)
[see item 2 above]. We wish to report some additional observations.

In 2009, a red squirrel on the Isle of Wight died after showing
respiratory distress. On postmortem examination, the tongue was
unremarkable apart from a small ulcer on the margin, but the
nasopharyngeal mucosa was inflamed and thickened, with many 1 to 2 mm
diameter whitish, plaque-like lesions. The laryngeal mucosa was also
thickened and covered in irregular whitish material. Froth was
present in the trachea, and both lungs appeared congested with
localised areas of consolidation and marginal emphysema.

Impression smears from the mucosal surface of the larynx and
nasopharynx revealed large numbers of both small and large
Gram-positive cocci plus smaller numbers of Gram-negative bacilli.
Cultures of larynx and lung yielded heavy growths of a large
Gram-positive coccus, which was identified by the RAPIDEC
(bioMerieux) test as _Staphylococcus aureus_. An additional small
Gram-positive coccus was isolated from larynx and lung after extended
culture. This could not be identified using API systems (bioMerieux).
Subsequent 16S rRNA sequence analysis suggested that the isolate
represents a previously undescribed bacterium showing only
approximately 93 per cent sequence similarity to members of the genus
_Granulicatella_.

Histological examination of the tongue, nasopharynx, and larynx
showed mucosal ulceration and necrosis of underlying tissues
associated with colonies of Gram-positive cocci. In consolidated
areas of lung there was fluid accumulation in alveoli and
infiltration by neutrophils and macrophages around foci of what
appeared to be plant material. It was concluded that the squirrel had
died of inhalation pneumonia and staphylococcal septicaemia secondary
to laryngeal ulceration and necrosis. The significance of the novel
coccus resembling _Granulicatella_ species is unclear.

As with the skin lesions described in red squirrels from the Isle of
Wight and Jersey [see item 2 above], the oral lesions in this
squirrel were considered to be most unusual. In view of this, the
staphylococcal isolates from the two 2008 cases with skin lesions and
that from this latest case were examined by multilocus sequence
typing (MLST). All 3 were shown to be _S aureus ST49_.

Interrogation of the _S aureus_ MLST database showed that this ST has
previously been associated with 2 human isolates and a single porcine
isolate (<http://saureus.mlst.net>; accessed 4 Jul 2010).

It is common practice for people on the Isle of Wight to provide the
squirrels with supplementary food, and this raises the possibility
that feeding stations may be contaminated by staphylococci of human
origin. We hope to carry out further investigations to determine
whether _S. aureus_ ST49 is part of the normal bacterial flora of red
squirrels or whether it is an opportunist pathogen, possibly of human origin.

